You can't dismiss for want of jurisdiction for failure to state a claim.(edited)
Brenda 2024-10-04 01:09 a.m.
(ignore that)
Brenda 2024-10-04 01:09 a.m.
"It is well settled that the failure to state a proper cause of action calls for a judgment on the merits, and not for a dismissal for want of jurisdiction. Whether the complaint states a cause of action on which relief could be granted is a question of law, and, just as issues of fact, it must be decided after, and not before, the court has assumed jurisdiction over the controversy. If the court does later exercise its jurisdiction to determine that the allegations in the complaint do not state a ground for relief, then dismissal of the case would be on the merits, not for want of jurisdiction." Swafford v. Templeton, 185 U. S. 487, 185 U. S. 493-494; Binderup v. Pathe Exchange, 263 U. S. 291, 263 U. S. 305-308.
